<subSubSection id="C34803C0DC791A7496E2B10D8B4CA148" pageId="28" pageNumber="201" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BED504BDC791A7496E2B10D8883A28C" blockId="28.[189,389,365,392]" box="[189,389,365,392]" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">
<heading id="D0A5E727DC791A7496E2B10D8883A28C" bold="true" box="[189,389,365,392]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="28" pageNumber="201" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B9268C59DC791A7496E2B10D8883A28C" bold="true" box="[189,389,365,392]" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">Natural History</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BED504BDC791A7496E2B1FF8B4CA148" blockId="28.[189,1399,412,579]" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">
The specimens were collected on the walls of a small cave. The wall of the cave is of clay material that came off on contact (
<figureCitation id="13694CCEDC791A7497AAB1DC8B56A2D1" box="[501,592,447,474]" captionStart="Figs 74–77" captionStartId="29.[189,242,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[195,1389,958,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-140@29.[189,1398,951,1782]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figs 74–77. Habitat and microhabitat of Physocyclys lyncis sp. nov. (74–75) and Physocyclus pocamadre sp. nov. (76–77). 74. Pine-oak forest, predominant vegetation in the Ejido La Primavera, Ecotourist Park, Zapopan, Jalisco, Mexico. 75. “Cueva del Lince” (type locality), inside of the Ejido la Primavera, Ecotourist Park, Zapopan, Jalisco, Mexico. 76. Habitat close to the beach “El Tecolote”, La Paz, Baja California Sur. 77. Xerophytic scrub, close to the beach “Punta San Francisquito” (type locality), Baja California." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484147/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
). This cave is located in perturbed oak forest, but the predominant vegetation of the Ejido La Primavera is oak-pine forest (
<figureCitation id="13694CCEDC791A749504B1818AB3A2F6" box="[859,949,482,509]" captionStart="Figs 74–77" captionStartId="29.[189,242,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[195,1389,958,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-140@29.[189,1398,951,1782]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figs 74–77. Habitat and microhabitat of Physocyclys lyncis sp. nov. (74–75) and Physocyclus pocamadre sp. nov. (76–77). 74. Pine-oak forest, predominant vegetation in the Ejido La Primavera, Ecotourist Park, Zapopan, Jalisco, Mexico. 75. “Cueva del Lince” (type locality), inside of the Ejido la Primavera, Ecotourist Park, Zapopan, Jalisco, Mexico. 76. Habitat close to the beach “El Tecolote”, La Paz, Baja California Sur. 77. Xerophytic scrub, close to the beach “Punta San Francisquito” (type locality), Baja California." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484147/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
). This 
<typeStatus id="54E9EEE9DC791A749259B1808D3FA2F6" box="[1030,1081,483,509]" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">type</typeStatus>
of vegetation is somewhat unusual for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C522BC8DC791A74979CB2658B55A12B" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[451,595,518,544]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Physocyclus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9268C59DC791A74979CB2658B55A12B" box="[451,595,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="201">Physocyclus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which commonly inhabits deciduous tropical forest and xerophytic scrub, but rarely temperate forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
